<body bgcolor="#ffffff">


<hr>
<h1><center>
CS39C Spring 1997<P>
Societal Issues in Communications and Computations
</center></h1>
<hr>

<a name="1"></a>
<h2>Discussion 1: <a href="overview.html">An Overview</a></h2>

<table width=475 border=0 cellspacing=2 cellpadding=2>
<tr>
<td width="45%">
<table border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1>
<tr><td><a href="http://www.eff.org/pub//Privacy/ITAR_export/HTML/hot.html">
        <img src="gifs/crypto.gif"></a></td>
    <td><a href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Censorship/HTML/hot.html">
        <img src="gifs/freespeech.gif"></a></td>
</tr>
<tr><td><a href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Intellectual_property/HTML/hot.html">
        <img src="gifs/intprop.gif"></a></td>
    <td><a href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Privacy/HTML/hot.html">
        <img src="gifs/privacy.gif"></td>
</tr>
</table>
</td>
<td width="55%">
In this <a href="overview.html"><b>overview discussion</b></a>, we will
introduce the various social, legal, and cultural issues that have
recently experienced a surge in interest and importance.  From cryptography
control to intellectual property, from digital cash to digital communities
- these types of issues have always existed, but they have been made much
more immediate and important since the dissemination of information
technology has been moving faster than legislation can regulate.
</td></tr>
</table>

<h4>Required Reading:</h4>

<a href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Net_culture/overhearing_the_internet.article">
<b>Overhearing the Internet</b></a>, an article by Neal Stephenson.

<h4>Optional Reading:</h4>
<a href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Net_culture/net.history"><b>The History of
the Net</b></a>,  a Master's Thesis by Henry Edward Hardy.

<a name="2"></a>
<h2>Discussion 2: <a href="crypto.html">Cryptography</a></h2>

<table width=475 border=0 cellspacing=2 cellpadding=2>
<tr>
<td width="45%">
<a href="http://www.cs.berkeley.edu/~iang/visprint.html">
<img src="gifs/sg_visprint.gif"></a>
</td>
<td width="55%">

<BLOCKQUOTE><B>
The lesson ... is that it is insufficient to protect ourselves with laws;
we need to protect ourselves with mathematics.  Encryption is too important
to be left solely to governments.
</B><P>
<i>--Bruce Schneier</i>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
Cryptography is the art, science, and mathematics of keeping messages
secure.  It is a foundation of electronic security, privacy-enhancing
technology, electronic commerce, and it is also a contentious legal issue
being debated by civil libertarians and governments around the world.  In
this seminar, you will be introduced to the basic terminology and
techniques behind cryptography, and some of the more interesting legal and
philosophical debates surrounding it.

<!-- <a href="crypto.html">Cryptography</a> -->

</td></tr>
</table>

<h4>Required Reading:</h4>

Chapter 1 of <b>Applied Cryptography</i>, by Bruce Schneier.  This
chapter will be handed out to you during class.

<h4>Optional Reading:</h4>

<a href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Privacy/Crypto_misc/crypto.intro">
<b>An Introduction to the Use of Encryption</b></a>, a tutorial by Peter Meyer.
<BR>
<a href="http://www.epic.org/crypto/">
<b>Electronic Privacy Information Center home page</b></a>, a site
dedicated to cryptographic policy.
<BR>
<a href="http://www.ddj.com/ddj/1996/1996.01/wagner.htm">
<b>Randomness and the Netscape Browser</b></a>, an explanation of
what can happen when cryptography is poorly implemented.
<P>

<a name="3"></a>
<h2>Discussion 3: <a href="crypto.html">The Freedom of the
Individual</a></h2>

<table width="475" border=0 cellspacing=2 cellpadding=2>
<tr>
<td width="55%">

This discussion session will focus on two different but related issues:
what you as an individual are <i>legally allowed</i> to do and what you as
an individual are <i>empowered to do</i>, with respect to privacy, free
speech, anonymity, and encryption).
<P>
The legislative efforts that currently restrict individual freedom are the
<a href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Alerts/s652_hr1555_96_draft_bill.excerpt">
Communications Decency Act (CDA)</a>, the
<a href="http://www.jya.com/eartoc.htm">Export Administration Regulations
(EAR)</a>, and the World
Intellectual Property Organization
<a href="http://www.wipo.org/eng/diplconf/distrib/treaty01.htm">(WIPO)
Copyright Treaty</a>.
<P>
The set of tools which we will discuss that help to give individuals the
ability to communicate securely and privately are <i>nym</i> servers,
anonymous remailers, anonymizing web proxies, and end-to-end encryption
tools such as PGP.

<!-- <a href="indiv.html">The Freedom of the Individual</a> -->

</td>
<td width="45%">

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1>
<tr><td align=center>
        <a href="http://www.eff.org/blueribbon.html">
        <img src="gifs/blueribbon.gif"></a></td>
    <td align=center rowspan=2>
        <a href="http://www.cdt.org/ciec/">
        <img src="gifs/cda.gif"></a></td>
</tr>
<tr><td align=center>
        <a href="http://www.eff.org/goldkey.html">
        <img src="gifs/privacy_online.gif"></a></td></tr>

<tr><td colspan=3 align=center>
       <a href="http://www.pgp.com">
       <img src="gifs/lock_key.gif"></a></td>
</tr>       
</table>

</td></tr>
</table>

<h4>Required Reading:</h4>

<a
href="http://www.cs.berkeley.edu/~daw/privacy-compcon97-www/privacy-html.html">
<b>Privacy-enhancing technologies for the Internet</b></a>, a paper
to appear in the 1997 CompCon Conference, authored by David Wagner and
Ian Goldberg.

<h4>Optional Reading:</h4>

None.

