<a name="5"></a>
<h2>Discussion 5: Society in the Large</h2>

<table width="475" border=0 cellspacing=2 cellpadding=2>
<tr>
<td width="55%">

The greatest impact that the communication and computation infrastructure
has had on the general populace is the ability for people to find and
communicate with each other, regardless of geographic location, resulting
in the emergence of the so called <i>virtual community</i> - is a forum in
which people of similar (and often highly specialized) interests can meet.
In addition to being a boon to already existing culture, the infrastructure
has led to the emergence of new &quot;cybercultures&quot;.  Counter- and
sub-cultures, such as the hacker underground, the cyberpunks, and the
digital activists, have seized upon the freedom and power of this new
technology to give themselves a powerful voice in today's society.

<!-- <a href="society_large.html"><b>society in the large</b></a> -->

</td>
<td width="45%">


<a href="http://www.well.com"><img src="gifs/home_image.gif"></a>

</td></tr>
</table>

<h4>Required Reading:</h4>

<a href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Net_culture/Virtual_community/well_figallo.article">
<b>The WELL: Small Town on the Internet Highway System</b></a>, an article by Cliff Figallo.

<h4>Optional Reading:</h4>
<ul>
     <li>
<a href="http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/eos/info/computer_ethics/www/index.html">
<B>Computer Ethics</b></a>, a site dedicated to all of the issues
surrounding Computer Ethics put together by a team of students from
<a href="http://www.ncsu.edu">North Carolina State University</a>.

     <li>
<a href="http://www.eff.org/CAF/cfp94.kadie.html">
<B>Applying Library Intellectual Freedom Principles to Public and
Academic Computers</B></a>, a talk presented at the 1994 Computers, Freedom,
and Privacy conference.
     <li>
<a href="http://www.cc.ubc.ca/appropriate-use/appropriate-use.txt">
<B>Report of the Task Force on the Appropriate Use of Information
Technology</B></a>, a quite liberal report put together by a team at the
<a href="http://www.ubc.ca">University of British Columbia</a> to
recommend a university wide policy on academic freedom, censorship,
and information technology.
     <li>
<a href="http://www.salon1999.com/30dec1995/features/mitnick1.html">
<B>Mitnick's Malice, Shimomura's Chivalry</B></a>, a glitzy but fun read
about the Kevin Mitnick vs. Tatsumo Shimomura hacking duel.  The famous
<a href="http://stargate.jpl.nasa.gov/~tak/misc/sleuth.html">John Markoff
New York Times article</a> about this affair is another good source of fun
reading.
     <li>
<a href="http://www.clas.ufl.edu/anthro/cyberanthro/decl-indep.html">
<B>A Declaration of Independence of Cyberspace</B></a>, the infamous
reactionary writings of John Perry Barlow that was distributed after
the passage of the CDA.
     <li>
<a href="http://dkcmzc.chemie.uni-mainz.de/information/BIGDUMMY_GUIDE/HTML/bdg_254.html#SEC257">
<B>A Slice of Life in My Virtual Community</B></a>, an article by Howard
Rheingold about virtual communities - very similar in theme to the WELL
article above.
</ul>
<P>

<a name="6"></a>
<h2>Discussion 6: <a href="ip.html">Intellectual Property</a></h2>

<table width=475 border=0 cellspacing=2 cellpadding=2>
<tr>
<td align=center width="45%">
<a href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Intellectual_property/HTML/hot.html">
<img src="gifs/wi_logo2.gif"></a>

</td>
<td width="55%">

<i>From the WWW Consortium:</i>
<P>
Networking
technology is requiring us to rethink and reinterpret existing intellectual
property law.  For instance, digital networks cache copies of documents to
improve performance -- is this infringement, should royalties be paid? If
it isn't an infringement because it is temporary, how long is temporary?
What happens if these cached copies decrease the hits a Web service sees,
and consequently the revenue it generates from marketing? Does a link to an
infringing copy of intellectual property constitute contributory
infringement, or is this well within the bounds of fair use?

<!-- <a href="ip.html">Intellectual Property</a> -->

</td></tr>
</table>

<h4>Required Reading:</h4>
<a href="http://www.hotwired.com/wired/4.01/features/white.paper.html">
<b>The Copyright Grab</b></a>, an article about intellectual property and
copyright issues by
<a href="http://info.berkeley.edu/~pam">Pamela Samuelson</a>.
<BR>
<a href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Publications/John_Perry_Barlow/HTML/idea_economy_article.html">
<B>Selling Wine Without Bottles: The Economy of the Mind on the Global
Net</B></a>, an article on intellectual property by John Perry Barlow.

<h4>Optional Reading:</h4>
<a href="http://www.cipe.org/e17/ip3_95.html">
<B>Protecting Intellectual Property: How New Democracies Stand to Gain</B>
</a>, another introductory article on intellectual property by
Griffith B. Price, Jr.
<BR>
<a href="http://www.eos.ncsu.edu/eos/info/computer_ethics/www/copyright/index.html">
<B>Patents and Copyrights</B></a>, a set of pages dedicated to exploring
all of the issues surrounding patents and copyrights, particularly from the
perspective of software.

